column1: After the Super Tuesday primaries, which Democratic candidate will have won the most pledged delegates?
column6: ['US Politics']
column11: Note: this is a probability question, asking for the top finisher, not a delegate share question! Pledged delegates are those delegates whose votes are determined by the outcome of the primaries (Bustle). More than 10 states will hold Democratic primaries or caucuses on Super Tuesday, 1 March 2016 (HowStuffWorks, NBC News). Recommended Questions After the Super Tuesday primaries, which Republican candidate will have won the most pledged delegates? Who will win the Democratic Party nomination for the US presidential election?

Hillary Clinton and Bernie Sanders go into the Tuesday nominating contests with equal numbers of pledged delegates; yet the Southern states that dominate the contest and award the greatest number of delegates more closely mirror the electorate of Nevada and South Carolina, states Clinton won decisively. With Clinton expected to repeat her strong showing among minority voters in Southern states, Sanders would need to win large margins over Clinton in Minnesota, Massachusetts, Colorado, and Oklahoma, in addition to his home states of Vermont, where he is predicted to do well. The larger states show the two in a close race, and it would be unlikely for Sanders to pull the wide lead in each needed to catch up with what is expected to be Clinton's wide margins across the south. However, Sanders strong organization resulted in a closer than expected showing in the Nevada caucus, and the caucus system could play to Sanders' advantage in those states. Ran a simple Bayesian analysis using existing polling data to estimate what percent of the vote each candidate will get in each Super Tuesday, then did a Monte Carlo simulation that takes into account the uncertainty in those estimates. Sanders' probability of ending up with more delegates was unmeasurably small. I gave him 1% just because my analysis was fairly simple, so there could be important factors or sources of uncertainty I'm not taking into account.
